TY  - JOUR
AB  - After a r&#xe9;sum&#xe9; of the previous discussion between J. M. Keynes and A. H. Hansen, it is shown that the error disappears when the definition of Mr. Keynes's units of goods is changed. On account of the changed definition the equations apply to profit levels instead of to price levels. Therefore, following Mr. Keynes's suggestion for stabilizing prices through control of the volumes of investments and savings will result in a constant profit level instead of in a constant price level. This is demonstrated by an example. Since changes in profits, rather than changes in prices, are the underlying causes for the business cycle, the value of the equations is enhanced by the new interpretation. On the other hand the equations are developed for a very simplified community. In order to make the equations valid for a more complex society certain factors, not taken into account at present, will have to be included in them.
AU  - R&#xfc;bner-Petersen, K.
