TY  - JOUR
AB  - John Law is commonly regarded as a warm proponent of paper money based upon land as security and as the author of the unfortunate Mississippi Bubble. This is due to the fact that the contributions which he made to the theory of money and banking given in two groups of documents--The Piedmont Memorials and the French Money and Banking Documents--have escaped the attention of most students. Analysis of these documents reveals that Law abandoned his ideas of paper money based upon land as security in favor of a system of paper money issued by a central semi-public bank and secured by a reserve of specie and commercial paper. Law was thus the first author, as far as it is known, to give a complete and logical exposition of the theories of modern bank paper money, bank credit operations, and reserve banking. In view of the significance of these contributions, our judgments of Law as an economic theorist are in need of revision.
AU  - Wasserman, Max J.
